    "explanation": "<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mbz24hv9/1e037a9f-55a9-4788-bcdc-f98dcf8aeba8/86cb7870-4aab-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz24hvb.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mbz24hv9/1e037a9f-55a9-4788-bcdc-f98dcf8aeba8/86cb7870-4aab-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz24hvb.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Advanced 2025 Paper 1 Online Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 1 English Explanation 1\"><div></div>Atoms H and Br are added across the double bond.<div></div>\n<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mbz263jt/92ad4cb0-7838-4bc8-b69c-7d44790ca492/b35a0690-4aab-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz263ju.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mbz263jt/92ad4cb0-7838-4bc8-b69c-7d44790ca492/b35a0690-4aab-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz263ju.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Advanced 2025 Paper 1 Online Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 1 English Explanation 2\">\n<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mbz2csh3/52dff1d8-c6e9-466d-aef0-aaaec1f93d45/6d75c370-4aac-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz2csh4.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mbz2csh3/52dff1d8-c6e9-466d-aef0-aaaec1f93d45/6d75c370-4aac-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz2csh4.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Advanced 2025 Paper 1 Online Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 1 English Explanation 3\"><div></div>Finkelstein the action is 1 an SN2 (Substitution Nucleophilic Bimolecular) relation mechanism that involves the exchange of one halogen atom for another. Here, $\\mathrm{Br}^{-}$is replaced by I.<div></div>In this reaction, I attacks the carbon atom attached to the halogen Br.<div></div>\nGeneral reaction:<div></div>$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n&amp; R-X+N a I \\rightarrow R-I+N a X \\\\\n&amp; X: C l / b r\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,(\\mathrm{NaCl}, \\mathrm{NaBr})\n\\end{aligned}\n$$<div></div><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mbz2ioyk/e3ed7dc6-4e55-47ba-a6bb-ea5493b69c0f/119991c0-4aad-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz2ioyl.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mbz2ioyk/e3ed7dc6-4e55-47ba-a6bb-ea5493b69c0f/119991c0-4aad-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz2ioyl.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Advanced 2025 Paper 1 Online Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 1 English Explanation 4\"><div></div><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mbz2j704/1fd80d20-4e40-4b69-91bd-9a6b104a56d5/1f89af40-4aad-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz2j705.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mbz2j704/1fd80d20-4e40-4b69-91bd-9a6b104a56d5/1f89af40-4aad-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz2j705.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Advanced 2025 Paper 1 Online Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 1 English Explanation 5\"><div></div>Swart reaction is the reaction used to synthesize alkyl fluorides from alkyl chlorides or bromides. It involves heating the alkyl halide (chloride or bromide) with a metal fluoride (AgF) to replace, the halogen $(\\mathrm{Cl}$ or Br$)$ with a fluorine atom.<div></div>$$\n\\text { Hero, } \\mathrm{Br}^{-} \\text {is replaced by } \\mathrm{F}^{-}\n$$<div></div>$$\n\\text { General reaction: }\n$$<div></div>\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n&amp; R-X \\quad + \\quad \\text { AgF } \\quad \\rightarrow R \\rightarrow F \\quad +\\operatorname{Ag} X \\\\\n&amp; (X =Cl, B r)\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,(\\mathrm{AgCl}, \\mathrm{AgBr})\n\\end{aligned}\n$$<div></div>\n<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mbz2pql2/e73e5eb4-e4e4-4f2d-8967-0b47adb970f8/d584e760-4aad-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz2pql3.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mbz2pql2/e73e5eb4-e4e4-4f2d-8967-0b47adb970f8/d584e760-4aad-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz2pql3.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Advanced 2025 Paper 1 Online Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 1 English Explanation 6\"><div></div><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mbz2q76j/8df8c105-6b72-412f-91f4-7e4980be1c1a/e256eab0-4aad-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz2q76k.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mbz2q76j/8df8c105-6b72-412f-91f4-7e4980be1c1a/e256eab0-4aad-11f0-923a-1595f23bdd58/file-jaoe38c1mbz2q76k.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Advanced 2025 Paper 1 Online Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 1 English Explanation 7\"><div></div>A) $C-X$ bond length in $P, Q$ and $R$ follows the order $Q &gt; R &gt; P $.<div></div>\nBond length order $C-F &lt; C - B r &lt; C-I$\nBond length increases with the size of the halogen atom. Iodine is/ larger than bromine, which is longer than fluorine. Therefore the C-I bond (Q) is longer than $C-B r$ bond $(P)$, which is longer than the C-F bond (R). The correct order is $Q&gt;P&gt;R$. So, the statement is not correct.<div></div>B) $C-X$, bond enthalpy in $P, Q$ and $R$ flows the order $R&gt;P&gt;Q$\nBond enthalpy is the energy required to break a bond stronger, bonds are shorter in length and require more energy to break the bond. The C-F bond (R) is the strongest and shortest bond, followed by $C -B r$ bond $(P)$, and the $C-I$ bond $(Q)$ is the weakest and longest loons. So, C-F Fond (R) requires higher energy to bond breaking. Its bond enthalpy is higher. C - I  bond (Q) is the weakest bond and its bond enthalpy is lower. The bond enthalpy of $C-B r(P)$ is intermediate between $R_1$ and $Q$.<div></div>$$\n\\text { So, the statement is correct. }\n$$<div></div>c) Relative reactivity toward $S_{N 2}$ reaction in $P, Q$ and $\\ R$ follows the order $P&gt;R&gt;Q$ <div></div>Reactivity towards. $S_{N^2}$, order is $C-I&gt;C-B r&gt;C-F$\n$Q&gt;P&gt;R$<div></div>$S_N 2$ reactions are favoured by less steric hindrance. The order of reactivity is $I&gt;B r&gt;C l&gt;F$, because larger halogens are better leaving groups. So, the correct order is $Q&gt;P&gt;R$. The statement is not correct.<div></div>D) PK value of the conjugate acids of the leaving groups In $P, Q$ and $R$ follows the order $\\quad R&gt;Q&gt;P$.<div></div>\n$$\n\\text { Leaving group } \\Rightarrow \\text { P }\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,Q \\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,R\n$$<div></div>$\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\mathrm{Br}^{-} \\,\\,\\,  \\mathrm{I}^{-}\\quad \\mathrm{F}^{-}$<div></div>$$\n\\text { Conjugate acids } \\Rightarrow  \\mathrm{HBr}\\,\\,\\, HI\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,HF\n$$<div></div>$$\n\\text { pka order conjugate acids } \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{HI}&lt;\\mathrm{HBr}&lt;\\mathrm{HF}\n$$<div></div>The acidity of the acids HBr, HI and HF, increases in the order HF &lt; HBr &lt; HI. So, the Orrder of pka is HI&lt; HBr &lt; HF orThe acidity of the acids HBr, HI and HF, increases in the order HF &lt; HBr &lt; HI. So, the Orrder of pka is HI&lt; HBr &lt; HF or<div></div>$Q &lt; P &lt; R$ or $R &gt; P &gt; Q$ :<div></div>\nSo, the given statement is not correct.<div></div>\nCorrect statement is (B).<div></div>\n\nAnswer: Option (B)",
