    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>Statement 1 : Bromobenzene upon reaction with Br$$_2$$/Fe gives 1, 4-dibromobenzene as the major product.</p>\n<p>and</p>\n<p>Statement 2: In bromobenzene, the inductive effect of the bromo group is more dominant than the mesomeric effect in directing the incoming electrophile.</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "Statement 1 is True, Statement 2 is True; Statement 2 is a correct explanation for Statement 1."
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "Statement 1 is True, Statement 2 is True; Statement 2 is a NOT correct explanation for Statement 1."
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "Statement 1 is True, Statement 2 is False."
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "Statement 1 is False, Statement 2 is True."
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1lg6ow6bf/ff85daa2-45dc-4401-b2e3-956a7a0fc47c/21c9fcb0-d557-11ed-a8c9-174ee3544ddd/file-1lg6ow6bg.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1lg6ow6bf/ff85daa2-45dc-4401-b2e3-956a7a0fc47c/21c9fcb0-d557-11ed-a8c9-174ee3544ddd/file-1lg6ow6bg.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0px auto;max-height:40vh\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2008 Paper 1 Offline Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 4 English Explanation 1\"></p>\n<p>Bromine orientation is controlled by its mesomeric effect. Its stabilisation of arenium ion by +M activity.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1lg6oxz2n/c1278a6b-ce60-4aed-88dc-7748ef4cae20/53cfc5f0-d557-11ed-a8c9-174ee3544ddd/file-1lg6oxz2o.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1lg6oxz2n/c1278a6b-ce60-4aed-88dc-7748ef4cae20/53cfc5f0-d557-11ed-a8c9-174ee3544ddd/file-1lg6oxz2o.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0px auto;max-height:40vh\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2008 Paper 1 Offline Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 4 English Explanation 2\"></p>\n<p>In bromobenzene, the inductive effect of the bromo group is more dominant than the mesomeric effect in directing the incoming electrophile at para position. As a result, only mono substitution of bromobenzene takes place.</p>",
    "topic": "haloarenes",
    "year": 2008,
    "yearKey": "iit-jee-2008-paper-1-offline",
    "difficulty": "medium"
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>Give reasons :</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9m3gc0/91d43c45-6814-4956-8c4d-06d715e6b3b4/8bc54700-b376-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9m3gc1.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9m3gc0/91d43c45-6814-4956-8c4d-06d715e6b3b4/8bc54700-b376-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9m3gc1.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 3 English 1\"></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9m4lgj/67cae95e-6759-4bb0-80b1-1e0fe284fac8/ab8a0f30-b376-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9m4lgk.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9m4lgj/67cae95e-6759-4bb0-80b1-1e0fe284fac8/ab8a0f30-b376-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9m4lgk.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 3 English 2\"></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9m5upj/3b897429-87a0-4e2d-9267-6f82bbaa3431/ce7e6c70-b376-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9m5upk.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9m5upj/3b897429-87a0-4e2d-9267-6f82bbaa3431/ce7e6c70-b376-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9m5upk.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 3 English 3\"></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9m71ld/0e1f685c-0af1-40bc-af1a-3be0b6ceed9a/ef9ef410-b376-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9m71le.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9m71ld/0e1f685c-0af1-40bc-af1a-3be0b6ceed9a/ef9ef410-b376-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9m71le.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 3 English 4\"></p>",
    "options": [],
    "correct_options": [],
    "answer": "<p>(A) (i) Due to formation of acid, HBr (ii) No reaction</p>\n<p>(B) (i) Bimolecular reaction occurs. (ii) No bimolecular reaction.</p>\n<p>(C) (i) Nitro group is both ortho and para directing in this case and N atom of NO group has a lone pair of electrons on it.</p>\n<p>(ii) In this case, nitro group is meta directing.</p>\n<p>(D) The reduction of central benzene ring will give stability to 3 four membered antiaromatic rings, producing a stable compound.</p>",
    "explanation": "<p>(A) (i) When (2-bromopropan-2-yl)benzene on \nreaction with aqueous ethanol, an ether is \nformed by replacement of bromide ion by \nethoxy ion. The products formed are an ether \nand an acid, hydrogen bromide. </p>\n<p>The presence of HBr makes the solution \nacidic.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9m8l8r/a1299e27-60ea-493d-991d-40dad274a3dd/1a9be5b0-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9m8l8s.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9m8l8r/a1299e27-60ea-493d-991d-40dad274a3dd/1a9be5b0-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9m8l8s.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 3 English Explanation 1\"></p>\n<p>(ii) The 1-bromo-4-(propan-2-yl)benzene does \nnot react with aqueous ethanol. Thus, solution \nis neutral in nature.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9m9edy/150b8280-0b8c-4735-aba5-85ca56280144/311f4b60-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9m9edz.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9m9edy/150b8280-0b8c-4735-aba5-85ca56280144/311f4b60-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9m9edz.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 3 English Explanation 2\"></p>\n<p>(B) (i) The reaction between given compound with \naqueous NaOH is an example of bimolecular \nreaction. The fluoride group at ortho position \nis replaced with hydroxy group. The fluoride \nion is liberated during the reaction. The rate \nof reaction is enhanced by the presence of \nelectron withdrawing groups at ortho and para \npositions.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9mam83/0497ba93-a001-4974-a79c-9a1bfd7d9f2a/52fc4530-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9mam84.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9mam83/0497ba93-a001-4974-a79c-9a1bfd7d9f2a/52fc4530-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9mam84.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 3 English Explanation 3\"></p>\n<p>(ii) In this case, a bimolecular reaction does not \noccur. Thus, fluoride ion does not get eliminated \nfrom the compound.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9mbr96/8ba6782a-573c-484b-ae2b-676fdedd9a1e/72ae21a0-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9mbr97.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9mbr96/8ba6782a-573c-484b-ae2b-676fdedd9a1e/72ae21a0-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9mbr97.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 3 English Explanation 4\"></p>\n<p>(C) (i) The nitrosobenzene on reaction with\nmixture of conc. HNO$$_3$$ and conc. H$$_2$$SO$$_4$$\nundergoes nitration. The nitrogen atom has a \nlone pair of electrons on it. Also, nitro so group \nis both ortho and para directing. Therefore, H \natoms at ortho and para will be replaced by \nnitro group producing mixture of ortho and \npara products.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9md5kd/a368c6d5-29e0-4022-9c01-55a19b657be5/998b51d0-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9md5ke.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9md5kd/a368c6d5-29e0-4022-9c01-55a19b657be5/998b51d0-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9md5ke.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 3 English Explanation 5\"></p>\n<p>(ii) The nitrobenzene on further nitration using \nthe mixture of conc. HNO$$_3$$ and conc. H$$_2$$SO$$_4$$, \nproduces dinitrobenzene, by substituting H \natom at meta position by nitro group.\nThe nitro group is electron withdrawing group \nand is meta directing in nature.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9mea6d/329e688e-b91a-46c5-b5ec-f602d2e65545/b8ea5350-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9mea6e.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9mea6d/329e688e-b91a-46c5-b5ec-f602d2e65545/b8ea5350-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9mea6e.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 3 English Explanation 6\"></p>\n<p>(D) The reaction of compound with hydrogen gas \nin presence of Pd/C as a catalyst, the compound \nundergoes reduction producing following \nproduct.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh9mfnuj/7916aed1-cc0b-4426-bbc0-8a70c4b31fde/df4904b0-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9mfnuk.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh9mfnuj/7916aed1-cc0b-4426-bbc0-8a70c4b31fde/df4904b0-b377-11f0-b034-2711d08df967/file-jaoe38c1mh9mfnuk.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2005 Mains Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 3 English Explanation 7\"></p>\n<p>In the given compound, there is a central \nbenzene ring attached to three four membered \nrings which further attached to terminal \nbenzene rings. The three 4 membered rings \nare antiaromatic in nature. During a chemical \nreaction, the rings will be undergoing reaction \nsuch that most stable product will be formed.</p>\n<p>When a central benzene ring will undergo \nreduction, the stability of three antiaromatic \nrings will be achieved. Thus, compound \nobtained is quite stable.</p>\n<p>If the reduction of one of the terminal benzene \nrings occurs, only one four membered \nantiaromatic ring will attain stability. Thus, \nthe compound produced will be less stable as \ncompared to that of first compound. </p>\n<p>Final Answer :</p>\n<p>(A) (i) Due to formation of acid, HBr</p>\n<p>(ii) No reaction</p>\n<p>(B) (i) Bimolecular reaction occurs.</p>\n<p>(ii) No bimolecular reaction.</p>\n<p>(C) (i) Nitro group is both ortho and para directing \nin this case and N atom of NO group has a lone \npair of electrons on it.</p>\n<p>(ii) In this case, nitro group is meta directing.</p>\n<p>(D) The reduction of central benzene ring will give \nstability to 3 four membered antiaromatic rings, \nproducing a stable compound.</p>\n<p>Hints :</p>\n<p>The reaction between (2-bromopropan-2-yl)\nbenzene with aqueous ethanol, produces an \nether with HBr which is an acid. Hence, the \nsolution becomes acidic in nature.</p>",
